name: methyl (1-(4-chloro)phenylsulfonyl) cyclopropane
Reason: The basic structure to consider is cyclopropane which has a melting point of -128 degrees Celsius. The addition of various substituents will affect this melting point. The phenylsulfonyl group is a large, rigid group that significantly raises the melting point due to increased van der Waals interactions and possible dipole-dipole interactions from the sulfonyl group, we can estimate this group contributes +150 degrees. The chloro substituent on the phenyl ring adds more mass and a slight dipole, which could further increase the melting point by approximately +10 degrees. The acetal group (-C(=O)OC) is polar and can form dipole-dipole interactions, but the steric hindrance it introduces may not raise the melting point as much as other polar functional groups, so we could estimate an increase of about +25 degrees due to this group. When adding up these contributions, we must consider that the effect of each substituent may not be strictly additive due to potential interactions between them; nevertheless, we will treat them as additive for this prediction.
